  <h1>Types of ADA Violations</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Title I: Employment discrimination</h2>
  <p>Title I applies to private employers, state and local governments, employment agencies, and labor unions with 15 or more employees. It prohibits discrimination in every aspect of employment: hiring, firing, pay, promotion, job assignments, training, and all other terms and conditions. The most common claims are failure to accommodate, wrongful termination, and retaliation.</p>
  <p>The key concept is the <strong>interactive process</strong>: when an employee requests an accommodation, the employer must engage in a good-faith dialogue to identify an effective accommodation. Refusing to participate in the interactive process &mdash; or denying a clearly reasonable accommodation &mdash; is itself an ADA violation.</p>
  <h2>Title II: State and local government</h2>
  <p>Title II applies to all programs, services, and activities of state and local governments regardless of size. It covers physical accessibility of government buildings, website accessibility, provision of auxiliary aids for effective communication, and program access. Claims are filed in federal court or with the DOJ. Money damages require proof of intentional discrimination; injunctive relief is available without that showing.</p>
  <h2>Title III: Public accommodations</h2>
  <p>Title III covers places of public accommodation &mdash; hotels, restaurants, retail stores, theaters, gyms, hospitals, doctor&rsquo;s offices, law offices, and more. It requires removal of architectural barriers where readily achievable, provision of auxiliary aids and services, and policy modifications. Website accessibility under Title III has produced a surge of litigation: courts in most circuits apply Title III to websites of covered entities.</p>
  <h2>Perceived disability</h2>
  <p>The ADA covers people <em>regarded as</em> having a disability even if they do not actually have one. If an employer treats someone as disabled and takes adverse action on that basis, the claim proceeds under the &ldquo;regarded as&rdquo; prong. This is particularly common in hiring cases where a disclosed medical history prompts rejection.</p>
